[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] A **line chart** or **line graph**, also known as **curve chart**, is a type of chart that displays information as a series of data points called 'markers' connected by straight line segments.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] It is a basic type of chart common in many fields.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] It is similar to a scatter plot except that the measurement points are ordered (typically by their x-axis value) and joined with straight line segments.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] A line chart is often used to visualize a trend in data over intervals of time – a time series – thus the line is often drawn chronologically.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] In these cases they are known as run charts.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Some of the earliest known line charts are generally credited to Francis Hauksbee, Nicolaus Samuel Cruquius, Johann Heinrich Lambert and the Scottish engineer William Playfair.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Line charts often display time as a variable on the x-axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Playfair was one of the first to visualize data this way.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] In 1786, he plotted ten years of money spent by the Royal Navy.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] He supplemented the chart with a detailed description, telling his readers how to interpret the change over time because they were unfamiliar with this form of abstract visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] In addition to line charts, Playfair invented and popularized bar charts and pie charts.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] In the experimental sciences, data collected from experiments are often visualized by a graph.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Such a table representation of data is a great way to display exact values, but it can prevent the discovery and understanding of patterns in the values.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] In addition, a table display is often erroneously considered to be an objective, neutral collection or storage of the data (and may in that sense even be erroneously considered to be the data itself) whereas it is in fact just one of various possible visualizations of the data.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Understanding the process described by the data in the table is aided by producing a graph or line chart of *speed versus time*.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Such a visualisation appears in the figure to the right.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] This visualization can let the viewer quickly understand the entire process at a glance.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] This visualization can however be misunderstood, especially when expressed as showing the mathematical function $v(t)$ that expresses the speed v (the dependent variable) as a function of time t .
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] This can be misunderstood as showing speed to be a variable that is dependent only on time.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] This would however only be true in the case of an object being acted on only by a constant force acting in a vacuum.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Charts often include an overlaid mathematical function depicting the best-fit trend of the scattered data.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] This layer is referred to as a best-fit layer and the graph containing this layer is often referred to as a line graph.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] It is highly unlikely that the experimental error in the data is negligible, yet the curve falls exactly through each of the data points.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] In either case, the best-fit layer can reveal trends in the data.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Further, measurements such as the gradient or the area under the curve can be made visually, leading to more conclusions or results from the data table.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] A true best-fit layer should depict a continuous mathematical function whose parameters are determined by using a suitable error-minimization scheme, which appropriately weights the error in the data values.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Such curve fitting functionality is often found in graphing software or spreadsheets.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/line-chart] Best-fit curves may vary from simple linear equations to more complex quadratic, polynomial, exponential, and periodic curves.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] Matplotlib was originally written by John D.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] Since then it has had an active development community and is distributed under a BSD-style license.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] Michael Droettboom was nominated as Matplotlib's lead developer shortly before John Hunter's death in August 2012 and was further joined by Thomas Caswell.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] Matplotlib is a NumFOCUS fiscally sponsored project.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] Matplotlib is used in scientific research as a tool for data visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] For example, the Event Horizon Telescope collaboration used Matplotlib to produce visualizations during the effort to create the first image of a black hole.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] Matplotlib also underpins the plotting functionality of many scientific Python libraries (for instance, pandas uses Matplotlib as its default backend for plotting).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] Its importance to the scientific community has been acknowledged by institutions such as NASA, which in 2024 awarded a grant to support Matplotlib’s continued development as part of an initiative to fund widely used open-source scientific software.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] In education and data science, Matplotlib is frequently used to teach programming and data visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] It integrates with Jupyter Notebook, allowing students and instructors to generate inline plots and interactively explore data within a notebook environment.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/matplotlib] Many educational institutions incorporate Matplotlib into their curricula for teaching STEM concepts, and it is widely featured in tutorials, workshops, and open online courses as a primary plotting library.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] A **plot** is a graphical technique for representing a data set, usually as a graph showing the relationship between two or more variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] The plot can be drawn by hand or by a computer.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] In the past, sometimes mechanical or electronic plotters were used.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] Graphs are a visual representation of the relationship between variables, which are very useful for humans who can then quickly derive an understanding which may not have come from lists of values.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] Given a scale or ruler, graphs can also be used to read off the value of an unknown variable plotted as a function of a known one, but this can also be done with data presented in tabular form.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] Graphs of functions are used in mathematics, sciences, engineering, technology, finance, and other areas.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] Plots play an important role in statistics and data analysis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] The procedures here can broadly be split into two parts: quantitative and graphical.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] Quantitative techniques are a set of statistical procedures that yield numeric or tabular output.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] These and similar techniques are all valuable and are mainstream in terms of classical analysis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] There are also many statistical tools generally referred to as graphical techniques.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] Graphical procedures such as plots are a short path to gaining insight into a data set in terms of testing assumptions, model selection, model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, outlier detection.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] Statistical graphics give insight into aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] Graphs can also be used to solve some mathematical equations, typically by finding where two plots intersect.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/plot-graphics] Types of graphs and their uses vary very widely.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Go to the end to download the full example code.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] This tutorial covers some basic usage patterns and best practices to help you get started with Matplotlib.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Matplotlib graphs your data on `Figure`s (e.g., windows, Jupyter widgets, etc.), each of which can contain one or more `Axes`, an area where points can be specified in terms of x-y coordinates (or theta-r in a polar plot, x-y-z in a 3D plot, etc.).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] The simplest way of creating a Figure with an Axes is using `pyplot.subplots`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Depending on the environment you are working in, `plt.show()` can be left out.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] This is for example the case with Jupyter notebooks, which automatically show all figures created in a code cell.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Here are the components of a Matplotlib Figure.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] The Figure keeps track of all the child `Axes`, a group of 'special' Artists (titles, figure legends, colorbars, etc.), and even nested subfigures.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] `subplots()` and `subplot_mosaic` are convenience functions that additionally create Axes objects inside the Figure, but you can also manually add Axes later on.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] For more on Figures, including panning and zooming, see Introduction to Figures.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] An Axes is an Artist attached to a Figure that contains a region for plotting data, and usually includes two (or three in the case of 3D) `Axis` objects (be aware of the difference between **Axes** and **Axis**) that provide ticks and tick labels to provide scales for the data in the Axes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Each `Axes` also has a title (set via `set_title()`), an x-label (set via `set_xlabel()`), and a y-label set via `set_ylabel()`).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] The `Axes` methods are the primary interface for configuring most parts of your plot (adding data, controlling axis scales and limits, adding labels etc.).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] These objects set the scale and limits and generate ticks (the marks on the Axis) and ticklabels (strings labeling the ticks).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] The location of the ticks is determined by a `Locator` object and the ticklabel strings are formatted by a `Formatter`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] The combination of the correct `Locator` and `Formatter` gives very fine control over the tick locations and labels.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Basically, everything visible on the Figure is an Artist (even `Figure`, `Axes`, and `Axis` objects).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] This includes `Text` objects, `Line2D` objects, `collections` objects, `Patch` objects, etc.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] When the Figure is rendered, all of the Artists are drawn to the **canvas**.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Most Artists are tied to an Axes; such an Artist cannot be shared by multiple Axes, or moved from one to another.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Plotting functions expect `numpy.array` or `numpy.ma.masked_array` as input, or objects that can be passed to `numpy.asarray`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Classes that are similar to arrays ('array-like') such as `pandas` data objects and `numpy.matrix` may not work as intended.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Common convention is to convert these to `numpy.array` objects prior to plotting.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Most methods will also parse a string-indexable object like a *dict*, a structured numpy array, or a `pandas.DataFrame`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Matplotlib allows you to provide the `data` keyword argument and generate plots passing the strings corresponding to the *x* and *y* variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] See Matplotlib Application Interfaces (APIs) for an explanation of the tradeoffs between the implicit and explicit interfaces.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] (In addition, there is a third approach, for the case when embedding Matplotlib in a GUI application, which completely drops pyplot, even for figure creation.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Matplotlib's documentation and examples use both the OO and the pyplot styles.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] In general, we suggest using the OO style, particularly for complicated plots, and functions and scripts that are intended to be reused as part of a larger project.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] However, the pyplot style can be very convenient for quick interactive work.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] You may find older examples that use the `pylab` interface, via `from pylab import *`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] If you need to make the same plots over and over again with different data sets, or want to easily wrap Matplotlib methods, use the recommended signature function below.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Most plotting methods have styling options for the Artists, accessible either when a plotting method is called, or from a "setter" on the Artist.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] In the plot below we manually set the *color*, *linewidth*, and *linestyle* of the Artists created by `plot`, and we set the linestyle of the second line after the fact with `set_linestyle`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Matplotlib has a very flexible array of colors that are accepted for most Artists; see allowable color definitions for a list of specifications.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Line widths are typically in typographic points (1 pt = 1/72 inch) and available for Artists that have stroked lines.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Similarly, stroked lines can have a linestyle.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Marker size depends on the method being used.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] `plot` specifies markersize in points, and is generally the "diameter" or width of the marker.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] `scatter` specifies markersize as approximately proportional to the visual area of the marker.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] `set_xlabel`, `set_ylabel`, and `set_title` are used to add text in the indicated locations (see Text in Matplotlib for more discussion).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] All of the `text` functions return a `matplotlib.text.Text` instance.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] These properties are covered in more detail in Text properties and layout.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Matplotlib accepts TeX equation expressions in any text expression.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] where the `r` preceding the title string signifies that the string is a *raw* string and not to treat backslashes as python escapes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Matplotlib has a built-in TeX expression parser and layout engine, and ships its own math fonts – for details see Writing mathematical expressions.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] You can also use LaTeX directly to format your text and incorporate the output directly into your display figures or saved postscript – see Text rendering with LaTeX.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] In this basic example, both *xy* and *xytext* are in data coordinates.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] There are a variety of other coordinate systems one can choose -- see Basic annotation and Advanced annotation for details.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] More examples also can be found in Annotate plots.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Legends in Matplotlib are quite flexible in layout, placement, and what Artists they can represent.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] They are discussed in detail in Legend guide.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Each Axes has two (or three) `Axis` objects representing the x- and y-axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] These control the *scale* of the Axis, the tick *locators* and the tick *formatters*.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Additional Axes can be attached to display further Axis objects.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] In addition to the linear scale, Matplotlib supplies non-linear scales, such as a log-scale.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Since log-scales are used so much there are also direct methods like `loglog`, `semilogx`, and `semilogy`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] There are a number of scales (see Scales overview for other examples).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] The scale sets the mapping from data values to spacing along the Axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] This happens in both directions, and gets combined into a *transform*, which is the way that Matplotlib maps from data coordinates to Axes, Figure, or screen coordinates.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Each Axis has a tick *locator* and *formatter* that choose where along the Axis objects to put tick marks.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Different scales can have different locators and formatters; for instance the log-scale above uses `LogLocator` and `LogFormatter`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] See Tick locators and Tick formatters for other formatters and locators and information for writing your own.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Matplotlib can handle plotting arrays of dates and arrays of strings, as well as floating point numbers.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] These get special locators and formatters as appropriate.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] For more information see the date examples (e.g.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] For strings, we get categorical plotting (see: Plotting categorical variables).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] One caveat about categorical plotting is that some methods of parsing text files return a list of strings, even if the strings all represent numbers or dates.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] If you pass 1000 strings, Matplotlib will think you meant 1000 categories and will add 1000 ticks to your plot!
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Plotting data of different magnitude in one chart may require an additional y-axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Such an Axis can be created by using `twinx` to add a new Axes with an invisible x-axis and a y-axis positioned at the right (analogously for `twiny`).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] See Plots with different scales for another example.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Similarly, you can add a `secondary_xaxis` or `secondary_yaxis` having a different scale than the main Axis to represent the data in different scales or units.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] See Secondary Axis for further examples.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Often we want to have a third dimension in a plot represented by colors in a colormap.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] These are all examples of Artists that derive from `ScalarMappable` objects.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] They all can set a linear mapping between *vmin* and *vmax* into the colormap specified by *cmap*.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Matplotlib has many colormaps to choose from (Choosing Colormaps in Matplotlib) you can make your own (Creating Colormaps in Matplotlib) or download as third-party packages.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Sometimes we want a non-linear mapping of the data to the colormap, as in the `LogNorm` example above.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] We do this by supplying the ScalarMappable with the *norm* argument instead of *vmin* and *vmax*.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] More normalizations are shown at Colormap normalization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Adding a `colorbar` gives a key to relate the color back to the underlying data.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Colorbars are figure-level Artists, and are attached to a ScalarMappable (where they get their information about the norm and colormap) and usually steal space from a parent Axes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Placement of colorbars can be complex: see Placing colorbars for details.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] You can also change the appearance of colorbars with the *extend* keyword to add arrows to the ends, and *shrink* and *aspect* to control the size.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Finally, the colorbar will have default locators and formatters appropriate to the norm.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] These can be changed as for other Axis objects.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] You can open multiple Figures with multiple calls to `fig = plt.figure()` or `fig2, ax = plt.subplots()`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] By keeping the object references you can add Artists to either Figure.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Multiple Axes can be added a number of ways, but the most basic is `plt.subplots()` as used above.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] One can achieve more complex layouts, with Axes objects spanning columns or rows, using `subplot_mosaic`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] Matplotlib has quite sophisticated tools for arranging Axes: See Arranging multiple Axes in a Figure and Complex and semantic figure composition (subplot_mosaic).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/quick-start] For more plot types see Plot types and the API reference, in particular the Axes API.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] A **scatter plot**, also called a **scatterplot**, **scatter graph**, **scatter chart**, **scattergram**, or **scatter diagram**, is a type of plot or mathematical diagram using Cartesian coordinates to display values for typically two variables for a set of data.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] If the points are coded (color/shape/size), one additional variable can be displayed.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] The data are displayed as a collection of points, each having the value of one variable determining the position on the horizontal axis and the value of the other variable determining the position on the vertical axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] The scatter diagram is one of the seven basic tools of quality control.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] According to Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis, the defining characteristic distinguishing scatter plots from line charts is the representation of specific observations of bivariate data where one variable is plotted on the horizontal axis and the other on the vertical axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] The two variables are often abstracted from a physical representation like the spread of bullets on a target or a geographic or celestial projection.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] While Edmund Halley created a bivariate plot of temperature and pressure in 1686, he omitted the specific data points used to demonstrate the relationship.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] Friendly and Denis claim his visualization was different from an actual scatter plot.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] Friendly and Denis attribute the first scatter plot to John Herschel.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] In 1833, Herschel plotted the angle between the central star in the constellation Virgo and Gamma Virginis over time to find how the angle changes over time, not through calculation but with freehand drawing and human judgment.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] Sir Francis Galton extended and popularized the scatter plot and many other statistical tools to pursue a scientific basis for eugenics.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] When, in 1886, Galton published a scatter plot and correlation ellipse of the height of parents and children, he extended Herschel's mere plotting of data points by binning and averaging adjacent cells to create a smoother visualization.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] Fischer, and other statisticians and eugenicists built on Galton's work and formalized correlations and significance testing.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] A scatter plot can be used either when one continuous variable is under the control of the experimenter and the other depends on it or when both continuous variables are independent.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] If a parameter exists that is systematically incremented and/or decremented by the other, it is called the *control parameter* or independent variable and is customarily plotted along the horizontal axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] The measured or dependent variable is customarily plotted along the vertical axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] If no dependent variable exists, either type of variable can be plotted on either axis and a scatter plot will illustrate only the degree of correlation (not causation) between two variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] A scatter plot can suggest various kinds of correlations between variables with a certain confidence interval.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] For example, weight and height would be on the y-axis, and height would be on the x-axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] Correlations may be positive (rising), negative (falling), or null (uncorrelated).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] If the dots' pattern slopes from lower left to upper right, it indicates a positive correlation between the variables being studied.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] If the pattern of dots slopes from upper left to lower right, it indicates a negative correlation.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] A line of best fit (alternatively called 'trendline') can be drawn to study the relationship between the variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] An equation for the correlation between the variables can be determined by established best-fit procedures.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] For a linear correlation, the best-fit procedure is known as linear regression and is guaranteed to generate a correct solution in a finite time.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] No universal best-fit procedure is guaranteed to generate a correct solution for arbitrary relationships.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] A scatter plot is also very useful when we wish to see how two comparable data sets agree to show nonlinear relationships between variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] The ability to do this can be enhanced by adding a smooth line such as LOESS.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] Furthermore, if the data are represented by a mixture model of simple relationships, these relationships will be visually evident as superimposed patterns.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] Scatter charts can be built in the form of bubble, marker, or/and line charts.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] For example, to display a link between a person's lung capacity, and how long that person could hold their breath, a researcher would choose a group of people to study, then measure each one's lung capacity (first variable) and how long that person could hold their breath (second variable).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] The researcher would then plot the data in a scatter plot, assigning "lung capacity" to the horizontal axis, and "time holding breath" to the vertical axis.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] A person with a lung capacity of 400 cl who held their breath for 21.7 s would be represented by a single dot on the scatter plot at the point (400, 21.7) in the Cartesian coordinates.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] The scatter plot of all the people in the study would enable the researcher to obtain a visual comparison of the two variables in the data set and will help to determine what kind of relationship there might be between the two variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] For a set of data variables (dimensions) *X*1, *X*2, ... , *X**k*, the scatter plot matrix shows all the pairwise scatter plots of the variables on a single view with multiple scatterplots in a matrix format.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] For k variables, the scatterplot matrix will contain k rows and k columns.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] A plot located on the intersection of ith row and jth column is a plot of variables *X**i* versus *X**j*.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] This means that each row and column is one dimension, and each cell plots a scatter plot of two dimensions.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] A **generalized scatter plot matrix** offers a range of displays of paired combinations of categorical and quantitative variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] A mosaic plot, fluctuation diagram, or faceted bar chart may be used to display two categorical variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/scatter-plot] Other plots are used for one categorical and one quantitative variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] An introduction to the pyplot interface.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Please also see Quick start guide for an overview of how Matplotlib works and Matplotlib Application Interfaces (APIs) for an explanation of the trade-offs between the supported user APIs.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] `matplotlib.pyplot` is a collection of functions that make matplotlib work like MATLAB.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Each `pyplot` function makes some change to a figure: e.g., creates a figure, creates a plotting area in a figure, plots some lines in a plotting area, decorates the plot with labels, etc.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The implicit pyplot API is generally less verbose but also not as flexible as the explicit API.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Most of the function calls you see here can also be called as methods from an `Axes` object.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] We recommend browsing the tutorials and examples to see how this works.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] See Matplotlib Application Interfaces (APIs) for an explanation of the trade-off of the supported user APIs.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] You may be wondering why the x-axis ranges from 0-3 and the y-axis from 1-4.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] If you provide a single list or array to `plot`, matplotlib assumes it is a sequence of y values, and automatically generates the x values for you.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Since python ranges start with 0, the default x vector has the same length as y but starts with 0; therefore, the x data are `[0, 1, 2, 3]`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] `plot` is a versatile function, and will take an arbitrary number of arguments.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] For every x, y pair of arguments, there is an optional third argument which is the format string that indicates the color and line type of the plot.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The letters and symbols of the format string are from MATLAB, and you concatenate a color string with a line style string.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The default format string is 'b-', which is a solid blue line.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] See the `plot` documentation for a complete list of line styles and format strings.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The `axis` function in the example above takes a list of `[xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax]` and specifies the viewport of the Axes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] If matplotlib were limited to working with lists, it would be fairly useless for numeric processing.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] In fact, all sequences are converted to numpy arrays internally.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The example below illustrates plotting several lines with different format styles in one function call using arrays.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] There are some instances where you have data in a format that lets you access particular variables with strings.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] For example, with structured arrays or `pandas.DataFrame`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Matplotlib allows you to provide such an object with the `data` keyword argument.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] If provided, then you may generate plots with the strings corresponding to these variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] It is also possible to create a plot using categorical variables.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Matplotlib allows you to pass categorical variables directly to many plotting functions.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Lines have many attributes that you can set: linewidth, dash style, antialiased, etc; see `matplotlib.lines.Line2D`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Here are the available `Line2D` properties.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] MATLAB, and `pyplot`, have the concept of the current figure and the current Axes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] All plotting functions apply to the current Axes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The function `gca` returns the current Axes (a `matplotlib.axes.Axes` instance), and `gcf` returns the current figure (a `matplotlib.figure.Figure` instance).
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Normally, you don't have to worry about this, because it is all taken care of behind the scenes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Below is a script to create two subplots.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The `figure` call here is optional because a figure will be created if none exists, just as an Axes will be created (equivalent to an explicit `subplot()` call) if none exists.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The `subplot` call specifies `numrows, numcols, plot_number` where `plot_number` ranges from 1 to `numrows*numcols`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The commas in the `subplot` call are optional if `numrows*numcols<10`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] You can create an arbitrary number of subplots and Axes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] If you want to place an Axes manually, i.e., not on a rectangular grid, use `axes`, which allows you to specify the location as `axes([left, bottom, width, height])` where all values are in fractional (0 to 1) coordinates.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] See Axes Demo for an example of placing Axes manually and Multiple subplots for an example with lots of subplots.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] You can create multiple figures by using multiple `figure` calls with an increasing figure number.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] You can clear the current figure with `clf` and the current Axes with `cla`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] If you are making lots of figures, you need to be aware of one more thing: the memory required for a figure is not completely released until the figure is explicitly closed with `close`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Deleting all references to the figure, and/or using the window manager to kill the window in which the figure appears on the screen, is not enough, because pyplot maintains internal references until `close` is called.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The `r` preceding the title string is important -- it signifies that the string is a *raw* string and not to treat backslashes as python escapes. matplotlib has a built-in TeX expression parser and layout engine, and ships its own math fonts -- for details see Writing mathematical expressions.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Thus, you can use mathematical text across platforms without requiring a TeX installation.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] For those who have LaTeX and dvipng installed, you can also use LaTeX to format your text and incorporate the output directly into your display figures or saved postscript -- see Text rendering with LaTeX.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] The uses of the basic `text` function above place text at an arbitrary position on the Axes.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] A common use for text is to annotate some feature of the plot, and the `annotate` method provides helper functionality to make annotations easy.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] In an annotation, there are two points to consider: the location being annotated represented by the argument `xy` and the location of the text `xytext`.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] Both of these arguments are `(x, y)` tuples.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] In this basic example, both the `xy` (arrow tip) and `xytext` locations (text location) are in data coordinates.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] More examples can be found in Annotate plots.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] `matplotlib.pyplot` supports not only linear axis scales, but also logarithmic and logit scales.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] This is commonly used if data spans many orders of magnitude.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] An example of four plots with the same data and different scales for the y-axis is shown below.
[src:matplotlib-plotting/tutorials-pyplot] It is also possible to add your own scale, see `matplotlib.scale` for details.
